RF Rockets Spotlight
September 9 at 9:14 AM ·

Library Spotlight: There are now 3 book drops conveniently placed throughout the school for students to easily return textbooks and library books without any contact. All books are quarantined for the currently recommended full 72 hours before being able to go to the next person. We are masked and wear gloves when handling the books. We ❤ our students' health and want everyone to enjoy our books and ebooks. More on a whole new place to get ebooks to come!!

The library, while not open to drop in students or study hall, is still a busy busy place!! The library is the go to place when classrooms get an unexpected cleaning. In addition, any student who needs to work with his/her aide gets plenty of space to work and talk out the lesson while staying masked and every table is thoroughly cleaned after each use. RFHS is dedicated to everyone's success and health at school.

Yearbooks are in! Here's the scoop (please share):

*In person hybrid students will receive them in their 7th hour class on Tuesday and Wednesday Sept 1st and 2nd.

*2020 Grads and full remote students will be able to pick them up at our "drive-through" yearbook stand on the s-curve on Thursday and Friday Sept 3rd & 4th from 2:30 - 4:30.

*If a 2020 grad has a sibling currently enrolled, that sibling may pick up their book for them at the "drive-through" pick up on Thursday/Friday or by contacting Mrs. Shore.

*We have a limited number of extra copies that will be for sale at the drive-through pick up location on Thurs/Fri. Cost is $65 and it is first come, first serve. Checks need to be made out to Rock Falls High School. Cash is also accepted. Sorry, we cannot take credit cards. Supplies are limited.

First of all I would like to start by saying that our students are amazing. There is complete buy-in to everything we are asking them to do on a daily basis and this is a credit to all of our families.
I also wanted to update everyone after our first week of school. Due to the new expectations from the Illinois Dept of Public Health we have had to send some students home based on their symptoms presented at school. However, I can report that, as of today, we have had zero confirmed cases of COVID-19.
This is a tribute to all of our students and staff following the protocol our Re-Open Team established prior to the start of the school year.
Please review the attachment from the IDPH so you are familiar with the policies we have to follow on a daily basis. If your student is suffering from any of these symptoms and they are new and not explainable, do not hesitate to keep your student home.

Have a great weekend!!

https://www.isbe.net/Documents/IDPH-COVID19-Exclusion-Decison-Tree.pdf

post_text:
I know that with all the new changes and expectations to how school looks during this time that things sometimes can be confusing or unclear. It is important to remember that whether a student is following the hybrid schedule or using the remote option - School Meets Everyday. Yes, students are not IN school everyday, but they are expected to be engaged and checking in with teachers everyday. On hybrid days where students are not on site and for all remote learners, students must check in with their 7th pd. teacher for attendance purposes. If students do not check in, they will be considered absent. Also, we highly recommend that all students follow their schedule on a daily basis and check in with their Google Classrooms.
Students have all been notified of this and are aware. Please help by reminding them to check in and be engaged academically everyday.

Proactive Coaching
August 13 at 10:31 AM ·

For many of the college and high school coaches we work with, the unexpected shutdown has given them the gift of some downtime. The most successful coaches are using it as an opportunity for growth - both personal and program. We have compiled a list of areas that could improve you as a coach and/or your program. If each coach on the staff would choose 2 or 3 different things and become an “expert” on those areas and be able to share it with the rest of the staff, think how much better we can become.
Here are just some examples from 4 categories:
Organization - Practice Planning - End of the season banquet
Technical - Skill progression and terminology (7-12) - Rules of motor learning
Relationships - Getting players to accept roles - Developing confidence in players
Leadership - Setting team behavioral standards - Positive traditions

If you would like the complete list, please email me - bruce@proactivecoaching.info

Proactive Coaching
August 13 at 10:31 AM ·

For many of the college and high school coaches we work with, the unexpected shutdown has given them the gift of some downtime. The most successful coaches are using it as an opportunity for growth - both personal and program. We have compiled a list of areas that could improve you as a coach and/or your program. If each coach on the staff would choose 2 or 3 different things and become an “expert” on those areas and be able to share it with the rest of the staff, think how much better we can become.
Here are just some examples from 4 categories:
Organization - Practice Planning - End of the season banquet
Technical - Skill progression and terminology (7-12) - Rules of motor learning
Relationships - Getting players to accept roles - Developing confidence in players
Leadership - Setting team behavioral standards - Positive traditions

If you would like the complete list, please email me - bruce@proactivecoaching.info

I wanted to update you on new information that was shared with us on July 23rd from the Illinois State Board of Education.
https://www.isbe.net/Documents/Fall-2020-Learning-Rec.pdf

They have decided that all students have the right to participate in any Extra-Curricular activities during the 2020-2021 school year. This means that if you choose the Remote Learning Option for your student(s) they will be able to participate in all sports/activities.

If you have already filled out the survey with the understanding your student could not participate in any sports/activities and would like to change your response, you will need to contact the main office on Monday at 815-625-3886. The office is currently closed today, Friday, July 24th.
If you haven't completed the survey, please make sure to provide your responses by Wednesday, July 29th by 9:00 am.

I hope this does not create more confusion, but this is a very fluid situation and we are trying to provide our best plan when we have the most up to date information.

post_text:
So I’m sitting here thinking about what I should be doing right now at 12:30 on this Memorial Day Sunday. I’d be at the high school going over last minute prep for our 2020 Graduation ceremony. Probably making sure we are all ready to celebrate your accomplishments in an appropriate manner.
I know that this has not been the plan for any of you to have to miss out on everything you had hoped for during your senior year. Athletics/plays/Prom... the list goes on and on. However, we are all proud of how you have handled yourselves and reached your goal of finishing your high school experience. You will be able to draw on this moment for the rest of your lives. You will be connected together more than any other graduating class in a very long time.
I wish we were together today and I look forward to June 25th and 26th to celebrate with all of you!
#RFRocketPride

As we end 2 months of no school/quarantine, I wanted to let everyone know that we are scheduling device return dates for next week. On Monday, May 18th, from 9:00-12:00 we will collect computers from Seniors and Juniors. Sophomores and Freshmen will turn in their computers on Tuesday, May 19th from 9:00-12:00.

We will follow the same procedures as we have for everything else. Cars will enter at the west parking lot and move around to the S-Curve. Students will enter the building at the cafeteria and exit on the south side.

More information to come as we get closer to Monday/Tuesday.
